\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The ungodly have no right to live, he said, save by the mercy of the chosen ones. If the princes would not exterminate the ungodly, he asserted, God would take their sword from them because the right to wield the sword belongs to the community. The source of the evil of usury, thievery and robbery, he said, were the princes and the masters who had taken all creatures into their private possession \endash  the fishes in the water, the birds in the air, the plants in the soil. And the usurpers, he said, still preached to the poor the commandment, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Thou shalt not steal,\u8221\'94 while they grabbed everything, and robbed and crushed the peasant and the artisan. \u8220\'93When, however, one of the latter commits the slightest transgression,\u8221\'94 he said, \u8220\'93he has to hang, and Dr. Liar says to all this: Amen.\u8221\'94 The masters themselves created a situation, he argued, in which the poor man was forced to become their enemy. If they did not remove the causes of the upheaval, how could things improve in times to come? he asked. \u8220\'93Oh, my dear gentlemen, how the Lord will smite with an iron rod all these old pots! When I say so, I am considered rebellious. So be it!\u8221\'94 (Cf. Zimmermann\u8217\'92s\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Peasant War,}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~II, p. 75.)}{ }
